The most important work on Logic from the school of Leibnitz is the Philosophia Rationalis of Wolf, first. published in lina. Wolf is regarded by Kont as the representative of the dogmatic philosophy. Philosophy with Wolf is the science ol things possible, sofar as they are possible, and contains three principal branches, Theology, Psychology, and Physics. The criterion ol the possible is the principle of contradiction. Whatever is not contradictory is possible ¹· Logia directa the mind in the knowledge of all being ; its principles being ' drawn on the one side from Ontology, on the other from Psychology. The Lapica Dooenr is defined by Wolf as a Practical Scienca; the Lepino Utens as an Art; the former· being acquired by reaching, the latter by practice. The details of Wolls Logia are principally Aristotelian, with one or· two ingenious but perverse retinements. Thus, he reduces subaltern opposition to a syllogism with an identical minor promise, and all immediate consequences to abridged hypothetical syl· logisrns. Induction he regards, like Archbishop Whately, as a syllogism with the major promise suppressed. Wolf is also the author of a smaller Logio in German, of which there is a good English translation, published 1111770.
